# Git: commit (and push) after substantive changes

When you change this repository in a way the user would expect to see on GitHub (track content, labs, scripts, assets, config, README), **finish with Git**:

1. `git status` — confirm what changed.
2. `git add` the relevant paths (or `git add -A` when the whole change set should ship).
3. `git commit` with a short, accurate message (imperative mood, mention track/lab scope when useful).
4. **`git push origin main`** when `origin` exists and network is available, unless the user explicitly asked for a local-only commit.

Do not leave intentional workshop edits uncommitted at the end of a task. If push fails (auth/network), say so and leave the commit locally.
